 In Java, comparing strings using the `==` operator and the `.equals()` method are two different approaches, each with their own use cases.

1. Using `==`:
The `==` operator compares the memory addresses where the two objects are stored. It checks if both references point to the same object in memory. This is known as reference equality.

Example:
```java
String str1 = new String("Hello");
String str2 = str1; // str2 points to the same object as str1
String str3 = new String("Hello"); // str3 points to a different object

if (str1 == str2) { // true, they point to the same object
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are equal.");
}
if (str1 == str3) { // false, they point to different objects
    System.out.println("str1 and str3 are equal.");
}
```

2. Using `.equals()`:
The `.equals()` method compares the content of the strings, checking if they have the same sequence of characters. It's known as value equality. By default, the `.equals()` method checks for both reference equality and content equality. However, you can override this behavior in your custom classes by implementing the `equals()` method in your class.

Example:
```java
String str1 = new String("Hello");
String str2 = new String("Hello"); // str2 points to a different object with the same content
String str3 = new String("World"); // str3 has different content

if (str1.equals(str2)) { // true, they have the same content despite different memory addresses
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 have the same content.");
}
if (str1.equals(str3)) { // false, different content
    System.out.println("str1 and str3 have the same content.");
}
```

In your case, using `==` would have worked because you were comparing string literals, which are stored in a special read-only memory section called string pool. All string literals have the same content and are stored in the same memory location, so `==` would return true. However, when you create strings using `new`, they are stored in the heap, and `==` would return false for different instances even if they have the same content. Using `.equals()` ensures that you compare the content of the strings regardless of where they are stored in memory.

In summary, use `==` when you want to check if two references point to the same object (reference equality), and use `.equals()` when you want to check if two strings have the same content (value equality). For most cases involving strings, it's recommended to use `.equals()` for clarity and correctness, especially when dealing with string objects created using `new`.

